6	 * The old estate lost the "~45s any website" crawl because the SPA-render tail carried a 45-second FLOOR
7	 * via `Math.max(45, ...)` / `Math.max(20000, Math.floor(deadlineMs*0.6))`, so a few shells always cost at
8	 * least that long; E-236 restored a 43s crawl to 6.9s by deleting the floor. Separately, an unbounded
9	 * browser step held a mint hostage for 752s. This gate fails CI (AST scan, evidence/ only) on:
10	 *
11	 *   1. A `Math.max(...)` FLOOR on a time/budget value: a Math.max with a numeric-literal argument that is
12	 *      budget-associated - the value it initialises is named timeout/budget/deadline/wait/delay/ttl/...,
13	 *      OR one of its arguments references such an identifier (e.g. Math.max(20000, f(deadlineMs))).
14	 *   2. A setTimeout delay / AbortSignal.timeout / budget-named constant that is a numeric literal > 120s
15	 *      (120000ms): a deadline longer than two minutes is a hang budget, not a cap.
16	 *
17	 * A Math.min cap, a setTimeout(fn, 5000), and a non-time numeric (a byte/char ceiling not bound to a
18	 * budget name) are all spared. Engine: acorn is MANDATORY; without it the gate REFUSES (exit 2) rather
19	 * than approximate (Constitution Rule 4). String literals are invisible to acorn, so no false hits.
20	 *
21	 * Modes (tools/lib/gate-cli.js dialect):
22	 *   node tools/domain-gates/budget-caps.js               scan evidence/, exit 1 on any floor/oversize
23	 *   node tools/domain-gates/budget-caps.js --json <path> also write findings JSON for the sweep normaliser
24	 *   node tools/domain-gates/budget-caps.js --calibrate   scan eval/calibration-known-bad/fixtures/ and
